                                        <h2 class="s-post-subtitle">Disadvantages of Arrays</h2>
                                        <p class="s-post-text">
                                            While arrays can be useful in many situations, they have certain disadvantages. For instance, searching is very slow in an unordered array, insertion is slow in an ordered array, and deletion is slow in both. Because arrays are immutable, the size of an array can’t be altered once initialized. This can make arrays rather inflexible when modeling real world data.

                                            Linked Lists are likely the second most commonly used data structure. They can replace arrays as the basis for other data structures such as stacks and queues. While Linked Lists aren’t the solution to all data storage problems, they are quite versatile and also rather simple to understand.


                                        </p>
